# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: html-templates
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:html-templates/api-shadowroot] This feature is well established and works across many devices and browser versions.
[src:html-templates/api-shadowroot] It’s been available across browsers since January 2020.
[src:html-templates/api-shadowroot] The **`ShadowRoot`** interface of the Shadow DOM API is the root node of a DOM subtree that is rendered separately from a document's main DOM tree.
[src:html-templates/api-shadowroot] You can retrieve a reference to an element's shadow root using its `Element.shadowRoot` property, provided it was created using `Element.attachShadow()` with the `mode` option set to `open`.
[src:html-templates/api-shadowroot] Returns the `Element` within the shadow tree that has focus.
[src:html-templates/api-shadowroot] Add an array of constructed stylesheets to be used by the shadow DOM subtree.
[src:html-templates/api-shadowroot] These may be shared with other DOM subtrees that share the same parent `Document` node, and the document itself.
[src:html-templates/api-shadowroot] A boolean that indicates whether the shadow root is clonable.
[src:html-templates/api-shadowroot] Returns the `CustomElementRegistry` object associated with this shadow root, or `null` if one has not been set.
[src:html-templates/api-shadowroot] A boolean that indicates whether the shadow root delegates focus if a non-focusable node is selected.
[src:html-templates/api-shadowroot] The element that's currently in full screen mode for this shadow tree.
[src:html-templates/api-shadowroot] Returns a reference to the DOM element the `ShadowRoot` is attached to.
[src:html-templates/api-shadowroot] Sets or returns a reference to the DOM tree inside the `ShadowRoot`.
[src:html-templates/api-shadowroot] The mode of the `ShadowRoot`, either `open` or `closed`.
[src:html-templates/api-shadowroot] This defines whether or not the shadow root's internal features are accessible from JavaScript.
[src:html-templates/api-shadowroot] Returns the `Element` within the shadow tree that is currently being presented in picture-in-picture mode.
[src:html-templates/api-shadowroot] Returns the `Element` set as the target for mouse events while the pointer is locked.
[src:html-templates/api-shadowroot] `null` if lock is pending, pointer is unlocked, or if the target is in another tree.
[src:html-templates/api-shadowroot] A nullable string value that indicates the effective target of any element reference made against the shadow host from outside the host element.
[src:html-templates/api-shadowroot] The value should be the ID of an element inside the shadow DOM.
[src:html-templates/api-shadowroot] If set, target references to the host element from outside the shadow DOM will cause the referenced target element to become the effective target of the reference to the host element.
[src:html-templates/api-shadowroot] A boolean that indicates whether the shadow root is serializable.
[src:html-templates/api-shadowroot] A serializable shadow root inside an element will be serialized by `Element.getHTML()` or `ShadowRoot.getHTML()` when its `options.serializableShadowRoots` parameter is set `true`.
[src:html-templates/api-shadowroot] This is set when the shadow root is created.
[src:html-templates/api-shadowroot] Returns a string containing the type of slot assignment, either `manual` or `named`.
[src:html-templates/api-shadowroot] Returns a `StyleSheetList` of `CSSStyleSheet` objects for stylesheets explicitly linked into, or embedded in a shadow tree.
[src:html-templates/api-shadowroot] Returns an array of all `Animation` objects currently in effect, whose target elements are descendants of the shadow tree.
[src:html-templates/api-shadowroot] Returns a `Selection` object representing the range of text selected by the user, or the current position of the caret.
[src:html-templates/api-shadowroot] Returns the topmost element at the specified coordinates.
[src:html-templates/api-shadowroot] Returns an array of all elements at the specified coordinates.
[src:html-templates/api-shadowroot] Provides an XSS-safe method to parse and sanitize a string of HTML into a `DocumentFragment`, which then replaces the existing tree in the shadow DOM.
[src:html-templates/api-shadowroot] Parses a string of HTML into a document fragment, without sanitization, which then replaces the shadowroot's original subtree.
[src:html-templates/api-shadowroot] The HTML string may include declarative shadow roots, which would be parsed as template elements the HTML was set using `ShadowRoot.innerHTML`.
[src:html-templates/api-shadowroot] An event fired when the node(s) contained in that slot change.
[src:html-templates/api-shadowroot] The following snippets are taken from our life-cycle-callbacks example (see it live also), which creates an element that displays a square of a size and color specified in the element's attributes.
[src:html-templates/api-shadowroot] Inside the `<custom-square>` element's class definition we include some life cycle callbacks that make a call to an external function, `updateStyle()`, which actually applies the size and color to the element.
[src:html-templates/api-shadowroot] You'll see that we are passing it `this` (the custom element itself) as a parameter.
[src:html-templates/api-shadowroot] In the `updateStyle()` function itself, we get a reference to the shadow DOM using `Element.shadowRoot`.
[src:html-templates/documentfragment] It’s been available across browsers since July 2015.
[src:html-templates/documentfragment] The **`DocumentFragment`** interface represents a minimal document object that has no parent.
[src:html-templates/documentfragment] It is used as a lightweight version of `Document` that stores a segment of a document structure comprised of nodes just like a standard document.
[src:html-templates/documentfragment] The key difference is due to the fact that the document fragment isn't part of the active document tree structure.
[src:html-templates/documentfragment] Changes made to the fragment don't affect the document.
[src:html-templates/documentfragment] Creates and returns a new `DocumentFragment` object.
[src:html-templates/documentfragment] Returns the amount of child `elements` the `DocumentFragment` has.
[src:html-templates/documentfragment] Returns a live `HTMLCollection` containing all objects of type `Element` that are children of the `DocumentFragment` object.
[src:html-templates/documentfragment] Returns the `Element` that is the first child of the `DocumentFragment` object, or `null` if there is none.
[src:html-templates/documentfragment] Returns the `Element` that is the last child of the `DocumentFragment` object, or `null` if there is none.
[src:html-templates/documentfragment] Inserts a set of `Node` objects or strings after the last child of the document fragment.
[src:html-templates/documentfragment] Inserts a set of `Node` objects or strings before the first child of the document fragment.
[src:html-templates/documentfragment] Returns the first `Element` node within the `DocumentFragment`, in document order, that matches the specified selectors.
[src:html-templates/documentfragment] Returns a `NodeList` of all the `Element` nodes within the `DocumentFragment` that match the specified selectors.
[src:html-templates/documentfragment] Moves a given `Node` inside the invoking `DocumentFragment` as a direct child, before a given reference node, without removing and then inserting the node.
[src:html-templates/documentfragment] Replaces the existing children of a `DocumentFragment` with a specified new set of children.
[src:html-templates/documentfragment] Returns the first `Element` node within the `DocumentFragment`, in document order, that matches the specified ID.
[src:html-templates/documentfragment] Functionally equivalent to `Document.getElementById()`.
[src:html-templates/documentfragment] A common use for `DocumentFragment` is to create one, assemble a DOM subtree within it, then append or insert the fragment into the DOM using `Node` interface methods such as `appendChild()`, `append()`, or `insertBefore()`.
[src:html-templates/documentfragment] Doing this moves the fragment's nodes into the DOM, leaving behind an empty `DocumentFragment`.
[src:html-templates/documentfragment] This interface is also of great use with Web components: `<template>` elements contain a `DocumentFragment` in their `HTMLTemplateElement.content` property.
[src:html-templates/documentfragment] An empty `DocumentFragment` can be created using the `document.createDocumentFragment()` method or the constructor.
[src:html-templates/documentfragment] The performance benefit of `DocumentFragment` is often overstated.
[src:html-templates/documentfragment] In fact, in some engines, using a `DocumentFragment` is slower than appending to the document in a loop as demonstrated in this benchmark.
[src:html-templates/documentfragment] However, the difference between these examples is so marginal that it's better to optimize for readability than performance.
[src:html-templates/element-slot] The **`<slot>`** HTML element is a placeholder inside a Web Component that you can fill with your own markup when the component is used.
[src:html-templates/element-slot] This lets you create separate DOM trees and present them together.
[src:html-templates/element-slot] Slots can contain plain text, other HTML elements, or other web components.
[src:html-templates/element-slot] A slot can also contain default content, which is displayed if the slot is not assigned other content when the web component is used.
[src:html-templates/element-slot] This element includes the global attributes.
[src:html-templates/element-slot] A *named slot* is a `<slot>` element with a `name` attribute, while an *unnamed slot* has no `name` attribute, and the name defaults to the empty string.
[src:html-templates/element-slot] When a shadow root uses named slot assignment, top-level child elements of its host are rendered in slots that have a matching name in their `slot` attribute.
[src:html-templates/element-slot] Slot names should be unique per shadow root: if you have two slots with the same name, all of the elements with a matching `slot` attribute are rendered in the *first* slot.
[src:html-templates/element-slot] All top-level child elements that don't have a `slot` attribute are rendered in the first unnamed `<slot>` element, which is referred to as the *default slot*.
[src:html-templates/element-slot] The `name` has no effect if the shadow root uses manual slot assignment.
[src:html-templates/element-slot] For more information see `shadowrootslotassignment` on the `<template>` element and `Element.attachShadow()`.
[src:html-templates/element-slot] This HTML shows how a number of named slots might be declared within a `<template>` element.
[src:html-templates/element-slot] Note that these slots are only used as slots when the template is used inside a shadow root.
[src:html-templates/element-template] It’s been available across browsers since November 2015.
[src:html-templates/element-template] The **`<template>`** HTML element serves as a mechanism for holding HTML fragments, which can either be used later via JavaScript or generated immediately into shadow DOM.
[src:html-templates/element-template] Creates a shadow root for the parent element.
[src:html-templates/element-template] It is a declarative version of the `Element.attachShadow()` method and accepts the same enumerated values.
[src:html-templates/element-template] Exposes the internal shadow root DOM for JavaScript (recommended for most use cases).
[src:html-templates/element-template] Hides the internal shadow root DOM from JavaScript.
[src:html-templates/element-template] Sets the value of the `clonable` property of a `ShadowRoot` created using this element to `true`.
[src:html-templates/element-template] If set, a clone of the shadow host (the parent element of this `<template>`) created with `Node.cloneNode()` or `Document.importNode()` will include a shadow root in the copy.
[src:html-templates/element-template] Sets the `customElementRegistry` property of a `ShadowRoot` created using this element to `null`, rather than the document's custom element registry.
[src:html-templates/element-template] This allows a scoped `CustomElementRegistry` to be attached later using `CustomElementRegistry.initialize()`.
[src:html-templates/element-template] Sets the value of the `delegatesFocus` property of a `ShadowRoot` created using this element to `true`.
[src:html-templates/element-template] If this is set and a non-focusable element in the shadow tree is selected, then focus is delegated to the first focusable element in the tree.
[src:html-templates/element-template] Sets the value of the `referenceTarget` property of a `ShadowRoot` created using this element.
[src:html-templates/element-template] Sets the value of the `serializable` property of a `ShadowRoot` created using this element to `true`.
[src:html-templates/element-template] If set, the shadow root may be serialized by calling the `Element.getHTML()` or `ShadowRoot.getHTML()` methods with the `options.serializableShadowRoots` parameter set `true`.
[src:html-templates/element-template] Sets the `slotAssignment` property of a `ShadowRoot` created using this element.
[src:html-templates/element-template] This is the declarative equivalent of the `slotAssignment` option of the `Element.attachShadow()` method.
[src:html-templates/element-template] Elements are automatically assigned to `<slot>` elements within this shadow root.
[src:html-templates/element-template] Elements with the `slot` attribute are assigned to the first `<slot>` in the template that has the corresponding `name` attribute.
[src:html-templates/element-template] If multiple elements specify the same slot name, they are all added to the first slot in the template that has that name, and rendered in the order they are declared.
[src:html-templates/element-template] All unnamed elements — elements that don't specify a `slot` attribute — are assigned to the default slot in the order they are declared.
[src:html-templates/element-template] This is the first unnamed `<slot>` in the template.
[src:html-templates/element-template] Elements are manually assigned to particular slot elements using `HTMLSlotElement.assign()`.
[src:html-templates/element-template] This element has no permitted content, because everything nested inside it in the HTML source does not actually become the children of the `<template>` element.
[src:html-templates/element-template] The `Node.childNodes` property of the `<template>` element is always empty, and you can only access said nested content via the special `content` property.
[src:html-templates/element-template] However, if you call `Node.appendChild()` or similar methods on the `<template>` element, then you would be inserting children into the `<template>` element itself, which is a violation of its content model and does not actually update the `DocumentFragment` returned by the `content` property.
[src:html-templates/element-template] Due to the way the `<template>` element is parsed, all `<html>`, `<head>`, and `<body>` opening and closing tags inside the template are syntax errors and are ignored by the parser, so `<template><head><title>Test</title></head></template>` is the same as `<template><title>Test</title></template>`.
[src:html-templates/element-template] There are two main ways to use the `<template>` element.
[src:html-templates/element-template] By default, the element's content is not rendered.
[src:html-templates/element-template] The corresponding `HTMLTemplateElement` interface includes a standard `content` property (without an equivalent content/markup attribute).
[src:html-templates/element-template] This `content` property is read-only and holds a `DocumentFragment` that contains the DOM subtree represented by the template.
[src:html-templates/element-template] The `Node.cloneNode()` and `Document.importNode()` methods both create a copy of a node.
[src:html-templates/element-template] The difference is that `importNode()` clones the node in the context of the calling document, whereas `cloneNode()` uses the document of the node being cloned.
[src:html-templates/element-template] The document context determines the `CustomElementRegistry` for constructing any custom elements.
[src:html-templates/element-template] For this reason, use `document.importNode()` to clone the `content` fragment so that custom element descendants are constructed using the definitions in the current document, rather than the separate document that owns the template content.
[src:html-templates/element-template] See the `Node.cloneNode()` page's examples for more details.
[src:html-templates/element-template] Note that the `DocumentFragment` container itself should not have data attached to it.
[src:html-templates/element-template] See the Data on the DocumentFragment is not cloned example for more details.
[src:html-templates/element-template] If the `<template>` element contains the `shadowrootmode` attribute with a value of either `open` or `closed`, the HTML parser will immediately generate a shadow DOM.
[src:html-templates/element-template] The element is replaced in the DOM by its content wrapped in a `ShadowRoot`, which is attached to the parent element.
[src:html-templates/element-template] This is the declarative equivalent of calling `Element.attachShadow()` to attach a shadow root to an element.
[src:html-templates/element-template] If the element has any other value for `shadowrootmode`, or does not have the `shadowrootmode` attribute, the parser generates a `HTMLTemplateElement`.
[src:html-templates/element-template] Similarly, if there are multiple declarative shadow roots, only the first one is replaced by a `ShadowRoot` — subsequent instances are parsed as `HTMLTemplateElement` objects.
[src:html-templates/element-template] Other attributes prefixed with `shadowroot` allow declarative customization of the `ShadowRoot`, such as controlling how slots are assigned.
[src:html-templates/element-template] First we start with the HTML portion of the example.
[src:html-templates/element-template] First, we have a table into which we will later insert content using JavaScript code.
[src:html-templates/element-template] Then comes the template, which describes the structure of an HTML fragment representing a single table row.
[src:html-templates/element-template] Now that the table has been created and the template defined, we use JavaScript to insert rows into the table, with each row being constructed using the template as its basis.
[src:html-templates/element-template] In this example, a hidden support warning is included at the beginning of the markup.
[src:html-templates/element-template] This warning is later set to be displayed via JavaScript if the browser doesn't support the `shadowrootmode` attribute.
[src:html-templates/element-template] Next, there are two `<article>` elements, each containing nested `<style>` elements with different behaviors.
[src:html-templates/element-template] The first `<style>` element is global to the whole document.
[src:html-templates/element-template] The second one is scoped to the shadow root generated in place of the `<template>` element because of the presence of the `shadowrootmode` attribute.
[src:html-templates/element-template] This example demonstrates how `shadowrootdelegatesfocus` is applied to a shadow root that is created declaratively, and the effect this has on focus.
[src:html-templates/element-template] The code first declares a shadow root inside a `<div>` element, using the `<template>` element with the `shadowrootmode` attribute.
[src:html-templates/element-template] This displays both a non-focusable `<div>` containing text and a focusable `<input>` element.
[src:html-templates/element-template] It also uses CSS to style elements with `:focus` to blue, and to set the normal styling of the host element.
[src:html-templates/element-template] The second code block is identical except that it sets the `shadowrootdelegatesfocus` attribute, which delegates focus to the first focusable element in the tree if a non-focusable element in the tree is selected.
[src:html-templates/element-template] Last of all we use the following CSS to apply a red border to the parent `<div>` element when it has focus.
[src:html-templates/element-template] When the HTML is first rendered, the elements have no styling, as shown in the first image.
[src:html-templates/element-template] For the shadow root that does not have `shadowrootdelegatesfocus` set you can click anywhere except the `<input>` and the focus does not change (if you select the `<input>` element it will look like the second image).
[src:html-templates/element-template] For the shadow root with `shadowrootdelegatesfocus` set, clicking on the text (which is non-focusable) selects the `<input>` element, as this is the first focusable element in the tree.
[src:html-templates/element-template] This also focuses the parent element as shown below.
[src:html-templates/element-template] This example shows how elements can be assigned to slots in a shadow DOM based on their `slot` attribute (matched against the slot's `name` attribute).
[src:html-templates/element-template] First we define an `<article>` element that presents title, metadata, and article body information.
[src:html-templates/element-template] The article contains a `<template>` element that will become a shadow root, because of the presence of the `shadowrootmode` attribute.
[src:html-templates/element-template] We don't need to set its `shadowrootslotassignment` attribute because named slot assignment is the default.
[src:html-templates/element-template] The template defines elements that have named slots for "header" and "meta" information, and an unnamed slot for "body" information.
[src:html-templates/element-template] The elements are styled differently so it is easy to differentiate them.
[src:html-templates/element-template] Inside the same host, below the template, we have four elements for populating the slots.
[src:html-templates/element-template] The `<span>` elements have `slot` attributes that match the `name` attributes on slots in the template, and will populate the corresponding slots.
[src:html-templates/element-template] The two `<p>` elements are unnamed, so are both inserted into the unnamed `<slot>` in the "body" element.
[src:html-templates/element-template] The example below should show the content of the slots displayed in the appropriate sections.
[src:html-templates/element-template] This example shows how elements can be assigned to slots in a shadow DOM using manual slot assignment.
[src:html-templates/element-template] With this approach, each element must manually be assigned to a particular slot.
[src:html-templates/element-template] There is no default assignment, so any slot that is not assigned will be empty.
[src:html-templates/element-template] This warning is later set to be displayed via JavaScript if the browser doesn't support the `shadowrootslotassignment` attribute.
[src:html-templates/element-template] Next, we define an `<article>` element that presents title, metadata, and article body information.
[src:html-templates/element-template] This contains a `<template>` element that will become a shadow root, because of the presence of the `shadowrootmode` attribute, and will use manual slot assignment because `shadowrootslotassignment="manual"` is set.
[src:html-templates/element-template] The template defines elements that have slots for "header", "meta", and "body" information, that can be separately referenced by their `id` attribute.
[src:html-templates/element-template] The JavaScript for manual slot assignment is shown below.
[src:html-templates/element-template] First the code gets the slots within the shadow root, then the text to be inserted, and finally assigns the text to the slot.
[src:html-templates/element-template] Note that you can only assign a node once to any particular slot, and that if you assign multiple nodes to a single slot using `HTMLSlotElement.assign()`, the order they are specified controls the order they are added.
[src:html-templates/element-template] The code displays the hidden support warning if slot assignment is not supported.
[src:html-templates/element-template] When a `DocumentFragment` value is passed, `Node.appendChild` and similar methods move only the *child nodes* of that value into the target node.
[src:html-templates/element-template] Therefore, it is usually preferable to attach event handlers to the children of a `DocumentFragment`, rather than to the `DocumentFragment` itself.
[src:html-templates/element-template] Since `firstClone` is a `DocumentFragment`, only its children are added to `container` when `appendChild` is called; the event handlers of `firstClone` are not copied.
[src:html-templates/element-template] In contrast, because an event handler is added to the first *child node* of `secondClone`, the event handler is copied when `appendChild` is called, and clicking on it works as one would expect.
[src:html-templates/htmlslotelement] The **`HTMLSlotElement`** interface of the Shadow DOM API enables access to the name and assigned nodes of an HTML `<slot>` element.
[src:html-templates/htmlslotelement] A string used to get and set the slot's name.
[src:html-templates/htmlslotelement] Sets the manually assigned nodes for this slot to the given nodes.
[src:html-templates/htmlslotelement] Returns a sequence of the nodes assigned to this slot.
[src:html-templates/htmlslotelement] If the `flatten` option is set to `true`, it returns a sequence of both the nodes assigned to this slot, and the nodes assigned to any other slots that are descendants of this slot.
[src:html-templates/htmlslotelement] If no assigned nodes are found, it returns the slot's fallback content.
[src:html-templates/htmlslotelement] Returns a sequence of the elements assigned to this slot (and no other nodes).
[src:html-templates/htmlslotelement] If the `flatten` option is set to `true`, it returns a sequence of both the elements assigned to this slot, and the elements assigned to any other slots that are descendants of this slot.
[src:html-templates/htmlslotelement] If no assigned elements are found, it returns the slot's fallback content.
[src:html-templates/htmlslotelement] Listen to these events using `addEventListener()` or by assigning an event listener to the `oneventname` property of this interface.
[src:html-templates/htmlslotelement] Fired on an `HTMLSlotElement` instance (`<slot>` element) when the node(s) contained in that slot change.
[src:html-templates/htmlslotelement] The following snippet is taken from our slotchange example (see it live also).
[src:html-templates/htmlslotelement] Here we grab references to all the slots, then add a slotchange event listener to the 2nd slot in the template — which is the one that keeps having its contents changed in the example.
[src:html-templates/htmlslotelement] Every time the element inserted in the slot changes, we log a report to the console saying which slot has changed, and what the new node inside the slot is.
[src:html-templates/htmltemplateelement] The **`HTMLTemplateElement`** interface enables access to the contents of an HTML `<template>` element.
[src:html-templates/htmltemplateelement] A read-only `DocumentFragment` which contains the DOM subtree representing the `<template>` element's template contents.
[src:html-templates/htmltemplateelement] A string that reflects the value of the `shadowrootmode` attribute of the associated `<template>` element.
[src:html-templates/htmltemplateelement] A boolean that reflects the value of the `shadowrootdelegatesfocus` attribute of the associated `<template>` element.
[src:html-templates/htmltemplateelement] A boolean that reflects the value of the `shadowrootclonable` attribute of the associated `<template>` element.
[src:html-templates/htmltemplateelement] A string that reflects the value of the `shadowrootcustomelementregistry` attribute of the associated `<template>` element, indicating that the declarative shadow root will use a scoped `CustomElementRegistry`.
[src:html-templates/htmltemplateelement] A boolean that reflects the value of the `shadowrootserializable` attribute of the associated `<template>` element.
[src:html-templates/htmltemplateelement] A string that reflects the value of the `shadowrootslotassignment` attribute of the associated `<template>` element.
